{{COI|date=August 2010}}
'''The Wisconsin Center for the Advancement of Postsecondary Education (WISCAPE)''' was established in 2001 on the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] campus by former UW–Madison Chancellor [[David Ward (university president)|David Ward]].<ref name=Heinen>Heinen, N. “A Rare Look Inward.” Madison Magazine, March 2001.</ref>
==Purpose== Ward envisioned the center as “a policy [[think tank]], not just an academic think tank,” that would promote cross-disciplinary research and scholarship on [[postsecondary education]], enhance professional development for those working at colleges and universities, and engage the public in a dialogue about the role of postsecondary education in a democratic society.<ref name=Heinen />
==Areas of focus== Local and national media have since highlighted the work of the center’s staff, scholars, and affiliates on a variety of postsecondary education issues, including [[Student financial aid in the United States|financial aid]],<ref name=Ziff>Ziff, D. “A Study on Grant Students.” Wisconsin State Journal, July 27, 2008. [http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_a1689412-c429-5708-b950-4e0013e5f245.html]</ref> trends in state funding for postsecondary education,<ref>College Connections: A Weekly Radio Program about Higher Education in Oklahoma. “Understanding Funding Trends,” October 20, 2007. [http://www.okhighered.org/college-connection/archives/CC-10-20-07.wma]</ref><ref>Redden, E. “Explaining State Spending on Higher Ed.” Inside Higher Ed, October 11, 2007. [http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/10/11/spending]</ref> returns to state investment in postsecondary education,<ref>Trostel, P. “State Fiscal Priorities Disturbing.” Wisconsin State Journal, November 16, 2006. [http://host.madison.com/news/opinion/article_33ade463-3021-53ad-9c63-eab8d5717667.html]</ref> college student transfer issues,<ref>[http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2009/04/17/transfer Moltz, D. “Why Reverse Transfer?” Inside Higher Ed, April 17, 2009]</ref><ref>Ashburn, E. “Disadvantaged Students Can Earn 4-Year Degrees With Key Supports, Study Finds.” The Chronicle of Higher Education, August 9, 2009. [http://chronicle.com/article/Disadvantaged-Students-Can/47972/]</ref><ref>Carey, K. “Carrots, Sticks and Transfer.” Inside Higher Ed, June 23, 2008. [http://www.insidehighered.com/views/2008/06/23/carey]</ref> community colleges,<ref>Viadero, D. “Community College a Research Puzzle. Education Week, September 2, 2009. [http://www.edweek.org/ew/toc/2009/09/02/index.html]</ref><ref>Wisconsin Public Radio. “Transforming America’s Community Colleges,” University of the Air, August 9, 2009. [http://clipcast.wpr.org:8080/ramgen/wpr/uoa/uoa090809.rm]</ref><ref>Finkelmeyer, T. “UW-Madison Profs Help Shape Bold Initiative for Community Colleges.” The Capital Times, July 20, 2009. [http://host.madison.com/ct/news/local/education/university/article_08c44697-6bd2-5f96-a374-842a6c3c9b22.html]</ref> de facto [[privatization]] of public universities,<ref>Jaschik, S. “’The True Genius of America at Risk.’” Inside Higher Ed, January 30, 2006. [http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2006/01/30/public]</ref><ref>Dillon, S. “At Public Universities, Warnings of Privatization.” The New York Times, October 16, 2005. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/16/education/16college.html?pagewanted=print]</ref><ref>Rivedal, K. “Can Universities Stay Public?” Wisconsin State Journal, September 14, 2005. [http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_94c5df2a-9703-50e7-aae0-d60d35444d32.html]</ref> gridlock in state policymaking,<ref>Stampen, J. “Rise Of Block Voting In The Wisconsin State Legislature One Reason For Public Policy Lull.” WisOpinion.com, August 7, 2007. [http://wisopinion.com/index.iml?mdl=article.mdl&article=9333]</ref><ref>Stampen, J. “Democrats Continue Legislative Gridlock.” WisOpinion.com, April 30, 2010. [http://www.wisopinion.com/index.iml?mdl=article.mdl&article=27639]</ref> the college presidency,<ref>Peterson, H. “Why Presidents Fail and How They Can Succeed.” The Chronicle of Higher Education, June 13, 2008. [http://chronicle.com/article/Why-Presidents-Fail-and/8058]</ref> federal college cost containment measures,<ref>Lederman, D. “Dubious Approach to Cost Containment.” Inside Higher Ed, July 19, 2007. [http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/07/19/costs]</ref> and the [[Wisconsin Covenant]].<ref>Foley, R. “Doyle’s College Plan Needs Money: Study Says State Should Provide Tuition Aid to Needy Wisconsin Covenant Students.” Wisconsin State Journal, January 22, 2009. [http://host.madison.com/news/article_9c5ab11c-65bc-5dde-9da0-04156b104518.html]</ref><ref>Perez, E. “State Urged to Fund Covenant: College Program is Not Doing Enough to Help Needy Students, Report Says.” Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, January 23, 2009. [http://www.jsonline.com/news/education/38199064.html]</ref><ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/news/opinion/29348789.html “Make a Deal With Kids.” Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, May 15, 2007]</ref><ref>Foley, R. “Doyle Higher Ed Plan Would Be Costly.” Wisconsin State Journal, May 12, 2007. [http://host.madison.com/news/local/article_de3bb52a-05bf-5a77-9520-3bf5fa5ebeff.html]</ref>
